{{Userspace draft|source=ArticleWizard|date=May 2014}} 

''Agriculture in Connecticut''

[[Agriculture]] played a major role in the early growth of [[Connecticut]] as one of the original 13 colonies that would form the United States of America, particularly in the [[Connecticut River]] valley which provided fertile soil, temperate climate and easy access to markets. As the [[Industrial Revolution]] helped focus capital on mercantile centers in the 19th century, Connecticut farmers over time ceded their relative economic and political influence. 
[[File:Farm auction. Derby, Connecticut, September 1940.jpg|thumb|A farm auction in Derby, Connecticut, September 1940.]]

In the 21st century, farming remains a relatively small but still significant industry in Connecticut, employing some 12,000 people as of 2010.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.are.uconn.edu/documents/economicimpacts.pdf |title=Economic Impacts of Connecticut<U+2019>s Agricultural Industry |publisher=University of Connecticut |accessdate=May 16, 2014}}</ref> Connecticut had nearly 6,000 farms with 437,000 acres of land as of 2012, producing $551 million in revenue that year.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.agcensus.usda.gov/Publications/2012/Full_Report/Volume_1,_Chapter_1_State_Level/Connecticut/st09_1_001_001.pdf |title=Connecticut Table 1. Historical Highlights: 2012 and Earlier Census Years |publisher=USDA Census of Agriculture |date=2012 |accessdate=May 18, 2014. |ref=USDA Census Table 1}}</ref>  In 2012, the total value of Connecticut farmland and buildings was $4.4 billion, down 3.5% from 2011.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://usda01.library.cornell.edu/usda/current/AgriLandVa/AgriLandVa-08-02-2013.pdf |title=Land Values 2013 Summary |publisher=U.S. Department of Agriculture via Cornell University |date=August 2013 |page=16 |accessdate=May 25, 2014}}</ref>

Ending years of steady declines, between 2002 and 2012 the number of Connecticut farms increased 43 percent,{{sfn|USDA Census Table 1}} with one possible cause an increased consumer appetite for [[local food|locally sourced food]], drawing some younger people to start up small farms.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://articles.courant.com/2014-03-23/news/hc-farm-survey-results-ct-20140322_1_new-farmers-agriculture-census-andy-billipp |title=Let It Grow: Connecticut Leads Farm Growth In New England |publisher=''Hartford Courant'' |date=March 23, 2014 |ref=Courant, March 23, 2014}}</ref> 

Connecticut farms received $141 million in federal subsidies between 1995 and 2012, including commodity programs, conservation payments, crop insurance, and disaster aid, ranking it 45th of the 50 states.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ec2-54-243-190-15.compute-1.amazonaws.com/region.php?fips=09000 |title=Connecticut Summary Information |publisher=Environmental Working Group |accessdate=May 25, 2014}}</ref>

==Agricultural policy==
===Connecticut Department of Agriculture===
The Connecticut Department of Agriculture steers agricultural policy at the state level, with membership-based farm bureaus and other nonprofits contributing to policy direction.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ct.gov/doag/cwp/view.asp?a=1366&q=258962 |title=About the Department |publisher=Connecticut Department of Agriculture |accessdate=May 21, 2004 |ref="About the Department"}}</ref> The department has several responsibilities: foster a healthy economic and environmental climate for farms; protect resources; enforce laws related to domestic animals; and promote the industry. The agency includes a commissioner's office; bureaus for regulation and inspection, aquaculture; and agricultural development and resource preservation; and an administrative arm overseeing a farmer's market in Hartford.{{sfn|"About the Department"}} 
[[File:Steven Reviczky and Connecticut Gov. Dannel Malloy at White Oak Farms in Stonington.jpg|thumb|Steven Reviczky (left) and Connecticut Gov. Dannel Malloy (center) at White Oak Farms in Stonington in November 2012]]

In 2011, Governor [[Dannel Malloy]] appointed Steven Reviczky as commissioner of the Department of Agriculture, with Reviczky previously executive director of the nonprofit Connecticut Farm Bureau Association from 2006 to 2011.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ct.gov/doag/cwp/view.asp?a=1366&q=259092 |title=Welcome from Commissioner Steven K. Reviczky |publisher=Connecticut Department of Agriculture |accessdate=May 21, 2014}}</ref> Reviczky chairs a Governor's Council for Agricultural Development charged with developing policies to encourage Connecticut residents to spend at least 5% of their food purchases on locally grown products by 2020.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ct.gov/doag/cwp/view.asp?a=3595&q=423842 |title=Governor's Council for Agricultural Development |publisher=Connecticut Department of Agriculture |accessdate=May 21, 2014}}</ref>

The state Department of Agriculture oversees several programs that provide direct funding for farms, including the:

*CT Grown Joint Venture Grant Program;
*Environmental Assistance Program;
*Farm Reinvestment Grant;
*Farm Transition Grant;
*Farm Viability Grant Program for Municipalities; and
*Specialty Crop Block Grant.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ct.gov/doag/cwp/view.asp?a=3260&q=398732&doagPNavCtr= |title=Agricultural Business Development & Assistance |publisher=Connecticut Department of Agriculture |accessdate=May 21, 2014}}</ref>

The state has also authorized one-time assistance programs, including the Production Loss Assistance Needed Today (PLANT) Grant program authorized in 2013 that provided funds for farmers impacted by storms and flooding.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.governor.ct.gov/malloy/cwp/view.asp?Q=535146&A=4010 |title=Gov. Malloy: PLANT Grants already helping state's farms recover and rebuild |publisher=Office of Governor Dannel P. Malloy |date=November 14, 2013 |accessdate=May 21, 2014}}</ref>

A state Bureau of Inspection and Regulation has oversight for a wide range of duties, including inspecting inputs like feed and fertilizer, as well as milk and produce produced for schools; animal control and health, including tracking West Nile virus and other communicable diseases; monitoring milk prices; and licensing agricultural and animal health facilities.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ct.gov/doag/cwp/view.asp?a=1367&q=259106&doagNav=|title=Bureau of Inspection and Regulation |publisher=Connecticut Department of Agriculture |accessdate=May 21, 2014}}</ref>

The department publishes varying reports on the sector, including a weekly agricultural report; listings of farms; and guides to assist agricultural businesses, farmers markets and new farmers.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ct.gov/doag/cwp/view.asp?a=3243&Q=523766&PM=1 |title=Agency Publications |publisher=Connecticut Department of Agriculture |accessdate=May 21, 2014}}</ref>

===Land conservation===
As the Connecticut economy expanded following World War II, developers accelerated purchases of farmland for conversion to residential and commercial developments. In 1978, the state established the Connecticut Farmland Preservation Program with the goal of protecting 130,000 acres of land from development, at least 85,000 of that amount as cropland.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ct.gov/doag/lib/doag/farmland_preservation_/draft_2013_Annual_Report_Summary_draft_6jd_kw_pubjensen.pdf |title=Farmland Preservation Program 2013 Annual Report Summary |publisher=Connecticut Department of Agriculture |accessdate=May 21, 2014 |ref=Farmland Preservation Annual Report}}</ref> Under the Connecticut Farmland Preservation Program, farms sell their local government a conservation easement to their property, providing cash to the farm and control for the town to ensure the land can be withheld from future development.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://connecticutlawreview.org/files/2013/02/Sheldon.NoFarmsNoFood.45Conn.L.Rev_.1045.pdf |author=Sheldon, Tara |title=No Farms, No Food: Local Taxation and the Preservation of Connecticut's Farmland |publisher=''Connecticut Law Tribune'' |date=February 2013 |accessdate=May 21, 2014 |ref=Sheldon, ''Connecticut Law Tribune''}}</ref>

As of 2013 under the direction of the state Department of Agriculture, the program had secured rights for land totaling more than 37,600 acres on nearly 300 farms.{{sfn|Farmland Preservation Annual Report}}

In 1986, the state authorized a Joint State-Town Farmland Preservation Program to encourage municipalities to create their own preservation programs.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.farmland.org/programs/states/documents/AFT_ConservationOptionsforConnecticutFarmland2006.pdf |title=Conservation Options for Connecticut Farmland |publisher=American Farmland Trust |date=2006 |page=10 |accessdate=May 21, 2024 |ref=American Farmland Trust, 2006}}</ref>

The Connecticut Department of Energy and Environmental Protection administers the Connecticut Open Space and Watershed Land Acquisition Grants Program, established in 1998 to help towns, conservation groups and water companies protect land deemed important, including farmland.{{sfn|American Farmland Trust, 2006}}

Despite those efforts, over a five year period between 1997 and 2002, Connecticut lost 12% of its farmland to development, the highest percentage of any state in the nation.{{sfn|Sheldon, ''Connecticut Law Tribune''}}

===Taxation of agricultural enterprises===
Under Connecticut Public Act 490, for the purposes of local property taxation farmland is assessed at use value rather than fair market value, with the law intended to protect farmers from higher taxes caused by escalating land values in Connecticut. Despite the law, farm property taxes across Connecticut rose 44% between 1997 and 2002, the second highest rate of increase in the Northeast over that period.{{sfn|Sheldon, ''Connecticut Law Tribune''}}

Under Connecticut law, farmers can claim exemptions from property taxes on machinery and equipment valued up to $100,000; temporary structures used in the agricultural process; livestock and produce; and in the case of aquaculture, vessels used for commercial fishing. Municipalities have the option of allowing a tax abatement of up to 50% for other farm property.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ct.gov/doag/cwp/view.asp?a=1366&Q=317762&PM=1&doagNav=%7C |title=Agricultural Laws and Regulations |publisher=Connecticut Department of Agriculture |accessdate=May 22, 2014}}</ref>

Connecticut exempts several farm products from sales tax, including fruit, vegetables, eggs, maple syrup, honey, cakes and pies.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ct.gov/doag/cwp/view.asp?a=1366&q=258986 |title=Farm Sales Tax |publisher=Connecticut Department of Agriculture |accessdate=May 23, 2014}}</ref> Farms are also exempt from paying sales tax on goods they purchase or lease that are used exclusively in the agricultural production process.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ct.gov/doag/cwp/view.asp?a=1366&q=259044 |title=Sales Tax Exemption for Farmers |publisher=Connecticut Department of Agriculture |accessdate=May 22, 2014}}</ref>

==Agricultural products==
In 1986, Connecticut created the Connecticut Grown Program to help farmers promote products to consumers who wish to buy locally. Other efforts to promote consumer awareness of local farms include a Farmers' Markets program; signage directing visitors to farms; a Farm-to-School program; a Farm-to-Chef program; crop seasonal availability calendars; and promotional boards focused on apples, milk, seafood and wine, among other products.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ct.gov/doag/cwp/view.asp?a=3243&q=398984 |title=DOAG: Connecticut Grown Program |publisher=Connecticut Department of Agriculture |accessdate=May 21, 2014}}</ref>
[[File:Dairy farm in Redding, Connecticut.JPG|thumb|After horticulture, milk is the top agricultural product in Connecticut.]]


The top 15 agricultural products of Connecticut by value as of 2012:

