Connecticut farmers increasingly are offering Community Supported Agriculture programs in which consumers purchase produce with an up-front payment for a full growing season. 

As of 2007, Connecticut ranked first nationally in direct market sales at $27,000 per farm, with 22.4% of farms selling directly to markets, the second highest percentage in the nation.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nera.umd.edu/Sept2012Meeting/Merrill.pdf |title=Northeast Agriculture |publisher=New Hampshire Department of Agriculture, Markets & Food |date=September, 2012 |accessdate=May 22, 2014}}</ref>

==Agricultural research==
The Connecticut Agricultural Experiment Station researches plants, pests, soil, and water. In addition to its main laboratory in New Haven, the Connecticut Agricultural Experiment Station operates outdoor laboratories at Lockwood Farm in [[Hamden, Connecticut|Hamden]]; Valley Laboratory in [[Windsor, Connecticut|Windsor]]; and Griswold Research Center in [[Griswold, Connecticut|Griswold]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ct.gov/caes/cwp/view.asp?a=2812&q=345002 |title=Facilities |publisher=Connecticut Department of Agriculture |accessdate=May 21, 2014}}</ref>

Major breakthroughs by the Connecticut Agricultural Experiment Station include developing in 1918 a hybrid corn in that would have a major impact on world agriculture; creating in 1940 the first organic fungicide to protect crops; and developing tests in 1984 to identify [[Lyme disease]] in the lab.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ct.gov/caes/lib/caes/documents/publications/caes_accomplishment_report.pdf |title=CAES Accomplishment Report |publisher=Connecticut Agricultural Experiment Station |accessdate=May 21, 2014 |ref=CAES Accomplishment Report}}</ref>

The [[University of Connecticut]] College of Agriculture, Health and Natural Resources runs the Storrs Agricultural Experiment Station.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.canr.uconn.edu/canr/SAES/StorrsAgriculturalExperimentStation.html |title=College of Agriculture, Health and Natural Resources |publisher=University of Connecticut |accessdate=May 29, 2014}}</ref>

==Agritourism==
Many Connecticut farms derive a portion of their revenue from tourists, with organizers having published a Connecticut Farm Map<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ctfarms.uconn.edu/ |title=Connecticut Farm Map |publisher=Connecticut Department of Agriculture |accessdate=May 21, 2014}}</ref> and trails highlighting wine, beer, and cheese producers; farmers markets;<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.buyctgrown.com/trails |title=Trails |publisher=Connecticut Department of Agriculture |accessdate=May 21, 2014}}</ref> and historic barns.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.connecticutmag.com/Connecticut-Magazine/August-2013/Connecticuts-New-Historic-Barn-Trail-Showcases-Agricultural-Treasures/ |author=Lapiana, Maria |title=Connecticut's New Historic Barns Trail Showcases Agricultural Treasures |publisher=''Connecticut Magazine'' |date=August 2013 |accessdate=May 21, 2014}}</ref>

Between July and October, agricultural fairs occur throughout the state,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ctagfairs.org/events.aspx |title=Events |publisher=Association of Connecticut Fairs |accessdate=May 21, 2014}}</ref> and many producers attend the [[The Big E|Eastern States Exposition]], held annually in September in [[West Springfield, Massachusetts]].

==Aquaculture==
While the aquaculture industry nationally is monitored by the U.S. Department of Commerce,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nmfs.noaa.gov/aquaculture/what_is_aquaculture.html |title=Welcome to the Office of Aquaculture |publisher=National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration |accessdate=May 22, 2014}}</ref> in Connecticut it is regulated by the state Department of Agriculture.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ct.gov/doag/cwp/view.asp?a=3768&q=451508&doagNav=%7C |title=Welcome to the Bureau of Aquaculture |publisher=Connecticut Department of Agriculture |accessdate=May 22, 2014}}</ref> In 2010, Connecticut's aquaculture industry produced 450,000 bushels of clams and 200,000 bushels of oysters, supporting about 300 jobs. As of 2010, the state leased 53,000 acres of waterbeds to aquaculture operators, and municipalities leased another 20,000 acres.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://northeastoceancouncil.org/wp-content/uploads/2013/03/Aquaculture-White-Paper.pdf author=Lapointe, George |title=NROC White Paper: Overview of the Aquaculture Sector in New England |publisher=Northeast Regional Ocean Council |date= March, 2013 |accessdate=May 22, 2014}}</ref>

==History==
===17th century===
Before the arrival of European settlers, [[Native Americans in the United States|Native Americans]] farmed portions of Connecticut, growing [[maize|corn]], [[bean]]s, and [[cucurbita|squash]], among other plants; and tilling land using stone hoes, bones, turtle shells and wood.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://archive.org/details/historyofconnect00jenk |last=Jenkins |first=Edward H. |title=''Connecticut Agriculture, History of Connecticut'' |date=1925 |year=1925 |ref=Jenkins |pages=291<U+2013>294}}</ref> Native American tribes in New England are thought to have rotated crops, allowed land to lie fallow, and cleared land for cultivation using fire.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://connecticuthistory.org/dynamic-tensions-conservation-and-development-up-to-the-1920s |author=Glaser, Leah |title=Dynamic Tensions: Conservation and Development up to the 1920s |publisher=ConnecticutHistory.org |ref=Glaser |accessdate=May 20, 2014}}</ref>

Colonial settlers assimilated some practices of Native American farmers, particularly their reliance on corn as a crop; the use of fish and marine mud as a [[fertilizer]]; and their gathering of wild-growing [[wild rice|"Indian rice"]], [[berry|berries]] and [[hemp]].

New settlers introduced their own practices such as clearing and plowing fields -- using wooden [[plough|plows]] sheathed with sheet iron or tin{{sfn|Jenkins|p=400}} -- and husbanding livestock to produce better yields.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://connecticuthistory.org/topics-page/agriculture/ |title=Agriculture |publisher=ConnecticutHistory.org |accessdate=May 18, 2014}}</ref> While the land comprising modern-day Connecticut was heavily forested, natural clearings existed as well that were suitable for cultivation. Early farmers had to contend with predators representing a threat to [[livestock]], including [[wolf|wolves]],{{sfn|Jenkins|p=296}} and relatively poor grass for [[dairy cattle]] that encouraged the breeding of [[pig|hogs]] for meat. Over time, towns would develop [[village green]]s on quality pasture land to better feed and protect livestock.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://connecticuthistory.org/the-connecticut-town-green/ |author=Gagnon, Amy |title=The Connecticut Town Green |publisher=''Connecticut Explored'' via ConnecticutHistory.org |date=Spring 2012 |accessdate=May 21, 2014 |ref=''Connecticut Explored'', Spring 2012}}</ref>
[[File:Twachtman John Connecticut Landscape.jpg|thumb|Connecticut's early settlers cleared land of trees and boulders, marking boundaries with stone walls not unlike the scene in John Twachtman's ''Connecticut Landscape''. ]]

As settlers organized townships along [[Long Island Sound]] and major rivers, some traded various articles to Native Americans for deeds to [[arable land]] in the interior sections of the state, leading to the establishment of new towns.{{sfn|Jenkins|p=301}} The [[glacier]]s that formed Connecticut's ridges and river valleys left boulders in their wake, which farmers uprooted for use in stone walls demarcating boundaries.{{sfn|UConn Libraries}}

Connecticut's produce increased in variety to include [[apple]]s, [[barley]], [[beetroot|beets]], [[carrot]]s, [[cabbage]], herbs, [[lettuce]],  [[oat]]s, [[onion]]s, [[parsnip]]s, [[pear]]s, [[pea]]s, [[radish]]es, [[turnip]]s, [[wheat]]{{sfn|Jenkins|pp=309-310}} and broadleaf tobacco.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://connecticutexplored.org/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/2011/11/Laboring-Shade-Summer11.pdf  |author=Hutchins, Dawn Byron |title=Laboring in the Shade |publisher=''Connecticut Explored'' |date=Vol.9 No.3, Summer, 2011 |accessdate=May 21, 2014 |ref=Hutchins, ''Connecticut Explored''}}</ref> Crops were vulnerable to a range of threats, including birds, rodents, insects, flooding, drought and [[blight]].{{sfn|Jenkins|1925|p=316}}

Farmers also enjoyed abundant years that resulted in gluts of corn and other crops, with Connecticut's early colonial government attempting without success varying mechanisms to maintain prices, including purchase pools that sought to eliminate middlemen.{{sfn|Jenkins|p=317}}

Early Connecticut farmers exported beef<ref>{{cite web |url=http://books.google.com/books?id=h2wCj5DsRCAC&printsec=frontcover&dq=history+of+agriculture+united+states&hl=en&sa=X&ei=uNR9U-O6NK7isASb44KgDQ&ved=0CDIQ6AEwAQ#v=onepage&q=connecticut&f=false  |author=Hurt, R. Douglas |title=''American Agriculture: A Brief History'' |publisher=Purdue University Press |date=2002 |page=51 |accessdate=May 22, 2014 |ref=Hurt}}</ref> and produce primarily to [[Boston]], with smaller amounts shipped to [[Barbados]], [[Jamaica]] and other [[Caribbean]] islands.{{sfn|Jenkins|p=320}}

Settlers cultivated [[tobacco]] as early as 1640,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://connecticuthistory.org/windsor-tobacco-made-in-the-shade/ |title=Windsor Tobacco: Made in the Shade |publisher=ConnecticutHistory.org |accessdate=May 22, 2014 |ref="Windsor Tobacco," ConnecticutHistory.org}}</ref> despite some prohibitions on its use. By the 18th century most restrictions were no longer on the books, and tobacco exports grew.{{sfn|Jenkins|pp=320-321}} In 1784, Connecticut implemented measures in a bid to ensure that only the best quality tobacco was packaged for export, assigning inspectors and holding them accountable.{{sfn|Jenkins|p=335}}

===18th century===
During the 100-year period spanning 1670 to 1759, the median Connecticut farm's livestock holdings had three horses, 13 cattle, 16 sheep and seven pigs, according to an analysis of probate records.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=BZRJSx3uMYEC&pg=PA63&lpg=PA63&dq=connecticut+hemp+1740+cordage&source=bl&ots=afx3dwhFOA&sig=tp0sYY0uO11tzf-bLZ4ORqaYrOw&hl=en&sa=X&ei=Tp9-U6G9EY3gsATflIGwCA&ved=0CEIQ6AEwAw#v=snippet&q=connecticut&f=false |author=Purvis, Thomas |title=''Colonial America to 1763'' |publisher=Facts On File Inc. |date=1999 |accessdate=May 22, 2014 |page=54 |ref=Purvis}}</ref>

Irish settlers introduced potatoes in Connecticut in 1720, but colonial farmers would be slow to adopt the crop.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=ig9-gbP_zXkC&pg=PA23&lpg=PA23&dq=connecticut+potatoes+introduced+1720&source=bl&ots=kI-16oaMfn&sig=Ia0FmimnHabbb0DQmk4C6YnoLgA&hl=en&sa=X&ei=w5t-U8GwG9O-sQT1roKgDg&ved=0CD8Q6AEwAg#v=onepage&q=connecticut%20potatoes%20introduced%201720&f=false |author=Lehman, Eric and Nawrocki, Amy |title=''A History of Connecticut Food: A Proud Tradition of Puddings, Clambakes and Steamed Cheeseburgers'' |publisher=The History Press |date=2012 |accessdate=May 22, 2014 |page=23}}</ref> Connecticut onion farmers had ample success exporting, both to neighboring colonies like New York as well as the Caribbean, with southwest Connecticut becoming a center of the industry.{{sfn|Jenkins|pp=329, 411}} Farmers in some parts of Connecticut made maple syrup and sugar, and pressed apple cider including fermented varieties.

As Connecticut's maritime industry grew from trade and fisheries, demand grew for good quality hemp for the manufacture of cordage. In 1740, families were ordered to sow at least a handful of hempseed in an effort to boost stocks over coming years.{{sfn|Purvis|p=63}}

In 1734, Connecticut legislators created incentives for the development of a cottage silk industry, during a run-up in prices; by 1750, horticulturist Nathaniel Aspinwall was planting mulberry trees to support silkworms.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://connecticutexplored.org/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/2010/09/CONNECTICUT-EXPLORED_CONNECTICUTS_MULBERRYCRAZE.pdf |author=Wyss, Bob |title=Connecticut's Mulberry Craze |publisher=''Connecticut Explored'' |date=Vol.8 No. 3 Summer 2010. |accessdate=May 21, 2014}}</ref> Ezra Stiles, president of Yale College from 1778 to 1795, further promoted the planting of mulberry trees, creating a homegrown silk industry that lasted until the middle of the 19th century when blight destroyed mulberry plantations.{{sfn|Jenkins|p=332-334}}

In 1750, Reverend Jared Elliot published what is thought to be the first advice book by a British colonist in North America on farming and husbandry, ''Essays Upon Field-Husbandry in New-England, as it is or may be Ordered.'' Among other items, the text addressed drainage, fertilizer, better plowing techniques and the advantages of smaller farms.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://connecticuthistory.org/jared-eliots-advice-book-promotes-agriculture-in-the-colonies/ |author=Izard, Holly |title=Jared Eliot Calls on Colonists to Change their Agricultural Practices |publisher=ConnecticutHistory.org |ref=Izard |accessdate=May 20, 2014}}</ref>

In the livestock trade in the latter half of the 18th century, pork continued to be produced in sufficient quantities for export, but Connecticut also increased its sheep herds to the point where it produced twice as many as the next two colonies combined, with wool deemed better than other colonies though still not on par with English wool.{{sfn|Jenkins|p=335}} In 1802, General David Humphreys imported Spanish merino sheep to his farm in Derby, greatly improving the breed in Connecticut; with British wool imports cut off in the early part of the 1800s, Connecticut's sheep herd grew quickly, to 400,000 animals by 1813.{{sfn|Jenkins|pp=400-401}} Cattle production improved with the increased practice of sowing grass seed and the introduction of clover, beginning around 1790.{{sfn|Jenkins|p=392}}

===19th century===
Despite limited success in exports, entering the 19th century Connecticut farmers generally adhered to a model of subsistence farming and barter, with poor roads hampering the transport of produce to market and Long Island and New Jersey farmers competing for trade with burgeoning New York City.{{sfn|Jenkins|p=349}} By one estimate, settlers had cleared two-thirds of the Connecticut's available land.{{sfn|Glaser}}

That would change in the first half of the century, in part due to Connecticut's own metropolitan centers swelling in size, as well as improved machinery that enabled farmers to plant and harvest more crops, including the Hawkes Plow manufactured in Hartford beginning in the 1830s.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://books.google.com/books?id=_H01AQAAMAAJ&pg=PA48&lpg=PA48&dq=hawkes+plow+hartford&source=bl&ots=RJtjT3KKu3&sig=FuNYccglyjuyMK1-WwMJ4BOZkLQ&hl=en&sa=X&ei=VEWHU4rSAYq-sQSOjoKoBQ&ved=0CCsQ6AEwAA#v=onepage&q=hawkes%20&f=false |title=''Twenty-Eighth Annual Report of the Secretary of the Connecticut Board of Agriculture'' |publisher=Hartford: The Fowler & Miller Co. |date=1894 |page=48 |accessdate=May 29, 2014}}</ref>

The tobacco industry also saw its first significant growth in the first half of the 19th century, as farmers in the Connecticut River valley and later the [[Housatonic River]] valley found success with their leaves as cigar wrappers. By 1810, cigar and plug factories were established in East Windsor and Suffield.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=OQInAQAAMAAJ&pg=PA144&lpg=PA144&dq=1810+cigar+%22east+windsor%22+connecticut&source=bl&ots=H5j1EJchrr&sig=pMkq2qKdVNqlqhM5w8o9s14umc4&hl=en&sa=X&ei=lOp9U4zuHMLJsQSPhoGgBA&ved=0CEkQ6AEwBA#v=onepage&q=1810%20cigar%20%22east%20windsor%22%20connecticut&f=false |author=DeVault, Samuel H. and Cance, Alexander E. |title=''The supply and distribution of Connecticut Valley cigar leaf tobacco'' |publisher=Massachusetts Agricultural Experiment Station |date=October 1919 |accessdate=May 22, 2014 |page=144 |ref=DeVault & Cance}}</ref>

Farmers also sought to introduce better stocks of cattle, including Devonshires beginning in 1819; Ayrshires in 1822; Guernseys in 1830; Shorthorns in 1835; Jerseys in 1846; and Holsteins some time after 1860.{{sfn|Jenkins|pp=392-394}} From 85,000 milk cows in the state as of 1850, the herd would increase to 128,000 by the end of the century.{{sfn|Jenkins|1925|p=398}}

By the middle part of the century, Litchfield County had a booming cheese production business that produced an estimated 2.7 million pounds annually, with Lewis Norton creating the country's first cheese factory that relied on curd from other farms in addition to his own cows. In 1857, Gail Borden would establish a condensed milk manufacturing company that would evolve into [[Borden (company)|Borden]]. In 1871, the Farmington Creamery was organized as a joint stock company to churn out butter, but after a brief spurt of growth competition from western creameries and the introduction of butter substitutes would stifle butter production in Connecticut by the end of the century.{{sfn|Jenkins|pp=395-397}}
[[File:HenryLeavittEllsworth.jpg|thumb|Henry Leavitt Ellsworth, deemed the father of the U.S. Department of Agriculture]]

Agricultural advances were occurring throughout the states, particularly in the south and west, and with Connecticut's soil comparatively poor, the state's farmers increasingly focused on producing perishable goods for nearby populations that would not be subject to competing products from other faraway locales. Increasingly, farmers in various parts of the state focused on a few cash crops that proved successful for export.{{sfn|Jenkins|pp=350-351}} Apple and peach orchards were blossoming by the middle of the century, but would be subject to the vagaries of pests, weather, and competitors in other states.{{sfn|Jenkins|p=406-407}}

Farmers also began to organize in associations and later granges in order to share ideas and coordinate in getting produce to markets, and to organize fairs. As early as 1794, a Society for Promoting Agriculture in the State of Connecticut was formed,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=C4Y_AAAAYAAJ&pg=PA400&dq=history+of+agriculture+united+states+connecticut&hl=en&sa=X&ei=yN59U-qKDejfsASPxYHIBg&ved=0CDIQ6AEwAQ#v=snippet&q=connecticut&f=false |author=True, Alfred C. |title=A History of Agricultural Education in the United States: 1785-1925 |publisher=U.S. Department of Agriculture date=July, 1929 |page=14 |accessdate=May 22, 2014 |ref=History of Agricultural Education, 1929}}</ref>  renamed in 1818 the Agricultural Society of New Haven. A similar group was started in Hartford in 1817 and in other counties of the state between 1839 and 1854.{{sfn|Jenkins|pp=355-359}} The organization extended to the town level, as farmers' clubs sprouted locally starting in Middletown in 1842.{{sfn|Jenkins|p=358}}

In 1839 as head of the U.S. Patent Office, Hartford resident [[Henry Leavitt Ellsworth]] secured the first Congressional appropriation in support of agriculture and established a bureau supporting the industry. Leavitt is regarded as the father of the [[United States Department of Agriculture|U.S. Department of Agriculture]], which was created in 1862 four years after his death.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.aghalloffame.com/hall/ellsworth.aspx |title=Henry Leavitt Ellsworth |publisher=National Agriculture Hall of Fame |accessdate=May 29, 2014}}</ref>

In 1845, the Cream Hill Agricultural School was founded in West Cornwall in Litchfield County, with a farm totaling 200 acres. The school touted its access to New York City on the Housatonic Railroad. Tuition was $200 a year for the some 22 students that attended annually on average. The school closed in 1869.{{sfn|Jenkins|p=362-363}}
[[File:PSM V43 D010 Samuel William Johnson.jpg|thumb|Samuel William Johnson, credited with helping spur the funding for land-grant universities in the United States, as well as agricultural experiment stations.]]

In 1846, John Norton and Benjamin Silliman opened a laboratory at Yale focused on scientific applications in agriculture. Norton would publish in 1850 ''Elements of Scientific Agriculture'', only to die two years later of tuberculosis. Norton's protege [[Samuel William Johnson]] would become a leading expert in agricultural education, organizing a national conference that contributed to the Morrill Land-Grant Colleges Act of 1862 that awarded states 30,000 acres of federal land to help fund the creation of agricultural and mechanical colleges.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.yalealumnimagazine.com/articles/2405 |last=Schiff |first=Judith |title=When Yale was a farming school |publisher=''Yale Alumni Magazine'' |date=March-April 2009 |ref=Schiff |accessdate=May 18, 2014}}</ref> Johnson has been dubbed "the father of the agricultural experiment station" in the United States,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ct.gov/caes/lib/caes/documents/publications/bulletins/b280.pdf |title=1875-1925 Semi-Centennial of the Connecticut Agricultural Experiment Station |publisher=Connecticut Agriculture Experiment Station |date=July, 1926 |ref=Semi-Centennial 1926}} </ref> 

Theodore Gold helped spearhead the 1853 formation of the Connecticut Agricultural Society, as well as the Connecticut Board of Agriculture that would follow in 1866.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=C4Y_AAAAYAAJ&pg=PA400&dq=history+of+agriculture+united+states+connecticut&hl=en&sa=X&ei=yN59U-qKDejfsASPxYHIBg&ved=0CDIQ6AEwAQ#v=onepage&q=connecticut&f=false |author=True, Alfred C. |title=''A History of Agricultural Education in the United States: 1785-1925'' |publisher=U.S. Department of Agriculture |date=July 1929 |page=38 |accessdate=May 22, 2014}}</ref>

Created by the the Connecticut General Assembly, the Board of Agriculture included the governor and a representative appointed by each county's agricultural society, giving the board wide latitude to pursue an agenda to benefit farming. The Board of Agriculture would serve as a springboard for the 1875 creation of the Connecticut Agricultural Experiment Station at Wesleyan University in Middletown, the first in the nation;<ref>{{cite web |url=http://ysm.research.yale.edu//article.jsp?articleID=319 |author=Greenwood, V<U+00E9>ronique |title=Amino Acids, Alleles, & Antibodies - The Work of the Connecticut Agricultural Experiment Station |publisher=''Yale Scientific'' |date=Winter 2004 |accessdate=May 29, 2014}}</ref> and the Storrs Agricultural School, which would serve as the foundation for the University of Connecticut.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uconn.edu/history/ |title=It Began With a Gift |publisher=University of Connecticut |accessdate=May 18, 2014.}}</ref> With the 1887 passage of the Hatch Act, Congress created a national system of agricultural experiment stations.{{sfn|Hunt |page=193}}

In 1867, organizers formed the National Grange of Patrons of Husbandry in Washington, D.C., with a Connecticut state grange formed April 15, 1875. By 1892 Connecticut granges would have some 10,000 members.{{sfn|Jenkins|p=383-384}}

In 1881, Augustus and Charles Storrs donated 180 acres of land in Mansfield for the creation of the Storrs Agricultural School, the site previously having housed orphans who lost parents in the Civil War. 

While Yale was initially the beneficiary of funds raised from the sale of land under the Morrill Act, in 1893 the Connecticut General Assembly transferred federal moneys to the Storrs school, which in 1889 changed its name again to the Connecticut Agricultural College.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://connecticuthistory.org/uconn-and-the-evolution-of-a-public-university/ |author=Stave, Bruce |title=UConn and the Evolution of a Public University |publisher=ConnecticutHistory.org |accessdate=May 29, 2014}}</ref>

===20th century===
In 1900, 46 percent of Connecticut's population had a hand in the agriculture business.{{sfn|UConn Libraries}}

With passage of the Smith-Lever Act in May 1914, federal funding was established for the creation and support of agricultural extension institutions nationally, connected with the land-grant universities created under the Morrill Act, with the goal of providing instruction and improving farming methods. 

In 1912, A.J. Brundage created the Mansfield Corn Club, considered a precursor the emergence of 4-H youth development programs across the nation.work undertaken across the state and nation.{{sfn|UConn Libraries}}

In 1917, Donald Jones revolutionized maize production in developing a hybrid seed corn.{{sfn|UConn Libraries}} By 1963, it was estimated that Jones' discovery had increased the national wealth by 10%.{{sfn|CAES Accomplishment Report}}

In 1925, the Connecticut Department of Agriculture replaced the longstanding state Board of Agriculture.
[[File:CDHistory1-984 - Flickr - USDAgov.jpg|thumb|A New London County family readies for milking in 1928]]

New techniques promulgated by the Connecticut Agricultural Experiment Station were already seeing widespread adoption, including the cultivation of [[Connecticut shade tobacco|shade tobacco]], so named for the tents erected over them to protect them from direct sunlight. After Indonesian farmers began to export tobacco wrappers with thinner leaves than U.S. varieties, Connecticut botanist W.C. Sturgis successfully reproduced the thinner leaf in what would come to be known as shade tobacco. After successive seasons of wet weather that dampened prospects for cultivation, by 1910 hundreds of Connecticut farmers were growing shade tobacco.{{sfn|Hutchins, ''Connecticut Explored''}}

In 1922, farmers formed the Connecticut Valley Tobacco Association, with members pledging to sell their entire crop to the association which would then warehouse it in an attempt to better control prices. 

By the middle of the 20th century, 16,000 acres of shade tobacco were under cultivation, with fields tended by laborers from the south and the Caribbean who worked long hours for little pay.{{sfn|Hutchins, ''Connecticut Explored''}}

Connecticut farmers suffered severe drought conditions between August 1964 and November 1967,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nrcc.cornell.edu/drought/CT_drought_periods.html |title=Connecticut Drought Periods |publisher=Northeast Regional Climate Center |accessdate=May 21, 2014}}</ref> While some harvests of higher-value crops like shade tobacco were saved due to irrigation, In Fairfield County, some 125 dairy farms lost 80% of their pasture grass, with wells on 30% of those farms failing by November that year. Statewide, pasture and hay yields were down 40% for dairy farmers.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://digitalcommons.uconn.edu/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?article=1032&context=saes |authors=Janes, Byron E. and Brumbach, Joseph J. |title=The 1964 Drought in Connecticut |publisher=''Storrs Agricultural Experiment Station'' |date=1965 |accessdate=May 21, 2014}}</ref>

==Major farms==
Connecticut has several large farms, including Kofkoff Egg Farms in Bozrah, which as of 2014 maintained 4.7 million chickens, employed some 300 people and produced $12 million in revenue for its most recent fiscal year.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.cga.ct.gov/2014/PDdata/Tmy/2014HB-05139-R000221-MOARK%20Kofkoff%20Egg%20Farms,%20LLC-TMY.PDF |title=Testimony of Moark LLC-Kofkoff Egg Farms |publisher=Connecticut General Assembly |date=February 21, 2014 |accessdate=May 22, 2014}}</ref> 

Major dairy producers include Laurel Brook Farm in North Canaan, which owns 2,500 acres for dairy production;<ref>{{cite web|url=http://virtualfarmtour.cabotcheese.coop/cabot/farm/laurel-brook-farm/ |title=Laurel Brook Farm |publisher=Cabot Creamery Cooperative |accessdate=May 22, 2014}}</ref> and Fairvue Farm in Woodstock, which has a herd of 1,600 cows.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://virtualfarmtour.cabotcheese.coop/cabot/farm/fairvue-farm/ |title=Fairvue Farm |publisher=Cabot Creamery Cooperative |accessdate=May 22, 2014}}</ref> 

Large produce operations include Baggott's Family Farms in East Windsor, which cultivates more than 2,000 acres of corn, perennials and other products.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.baggottfarms.net/id524.html |title=Baggott ... Family ... Farms |publisher=Baggott Family Farms |accessdate=May 22, 2014}}</ref>

